To know the schema ID in the Registry of a message the producer first needs to know what the schema of the message looks like, to do so at least with the Java Avro&#39;s serializer the producer makes use of reflection to get the schema description which it then uses to request its id in the Registry.

The Schema Registry code is open source so you can see that the logic I mention looks something like [this][1]:

```
 @Override
  public byte[] serialize(String topic, Headers headers, Object record) {
    if (record == null) {
      return null;
    }
    AvroSchema schema = new AvroSchema(
        AvroSchemaUtils.getSchema(record, useSchemaReflection,
            avroReflectionAllowNull, removeJavaProperties));
    return serializeImpl(
        getSubjectName(topic, isKey, record, schema), topic, headers, record, schema);
  }
```
And once generated the schema is kept in cache, so if the schema extracted locally from the message object class that is about to be sent is not present in memory it is computed and [saved in the cache][2] to prevent future reprocessing.

```
private final ClassValueCache&lt;Schema&gt; schemaClassCache = new ClassValueCache&lt;&gt;(c -&gt; createSchema(c, new HashMap&lt;&gt;()));

/** Find the schema for a Java type. */
  public Schema getSchema(java.lang.reflect.Type type) {
    try {
      if (type instanceof Class) {
        return schemaClassCache.apply((Class&lt;?&gt;) type);
      }
